Design

> <span key="9a7809402fca49ef98023ec585215f2a"><span offset-key="9a7809402fca49ef98023ec585215f2a:0">Design is not just what it looks like and feels like. Design is how it works.</span></span>

<span key="bd22bef54e2d44568f70aabbff0b12be"><span offset-key="bd22bef54e2d44568f70aabbff0b12be:0">I can't call myself a designer yet but I am learning.</span></span>

<span key="e100fe68b9784df480195bc1b49860c0"><span offset-key="e100fe68b9784df480195bc1b49860c0:0">I do think design applies to everything I am doing. Even this wiki has some </span>*design choices*<span offset-key="e100fe68b9784df480195bc1b49860c0:2"> of how it can be structured. As the quote above says, it's not </span>*how it looks like*<span offset-key="e100fe68b9784df480195bc1b49860c0:4">, it's </span>*how it works*<span offset-key="e100fe68b9784df480195bc1b49860c0:6">.</span></span>

<span key="9a65bdc6054d4569a9eefc4d4679ccfa"><span offset-key="9a65bdc6054d4569a9eefc4d4679ccfa:0">Thus I try to be conscious of how my design decisions affect what I do. I like to use </span></span><a href="https://www.sketchapp.com" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="ffd3d9a5a9784c1a8fb88bc1682ec05f" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-4808_259-4809-237__"><span data-key="adea6d10a4dc45efbce752bf95c35177"><span data-offset-key="adea6d10a4dc45efbce752bf95c35177:0">Sketch</span></span></span></a><span key="5b86d5e1eef54a99b11e9b5d8e43aab3"><span offset-key="5b86d5e1eef54a99b11e9b5d8e43aab3:0"> and </span></span><a href="https://www.figma.com" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="5dc730c833984063bc19a84c04409a1a" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-4808_259-4809-237__"><span data-key="a11c34b63294467889b78fcd49671bb8"><span data-offset-key="a11c34b63294467889b78fcd49671bb8:0">Figma</span></span></span></a><span key="6f3d3ef6ed994029847fd115972534fe"><span offset-key="6f3d3ef6ed994029847fd115972534fe:0"> when designing things.</span></span>

Not “make it look pretty” but “surface.” I have had many interactions with smart educated people (even designers!) whom seem to believe design is art, that design is mainly about surface (e.g. “a designer chair.”)</span></span></span></a><span key="1eab28568f0e4612adc0e5d7a3d97181"><span offset-key="1eab28568f0e4612adc0e5d7a3d97181:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">​</span></span></span>
